for fixed document+taxonomy, record provider raw outputs and final labels; assert final-label changes only co-occur with provider response changes, and flag unexplained label drift.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.0,"Integration":0.03,"System":0.12,"Agentic":0.83,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Request construction enforces the configured token budget before dispatch (for example truncate/reject according to policy).","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure typically occurs where config + tokenizer/counting + request builder interact before provider call (MOCK-MISS=yes for cross-module handoff). Can be caught with in-process wiring and a stub dispatch sink (REAL-INFRA=no). Does not require real model output quality (LLM-DEP=no). No multi-agent sequence (MULTI-STEP=no). Rejection gate: System disqualified because enforcement is pre-dispatch by behavior text; Agentic disqualified because model judgment is irrelevant.","test_description":"Configure small budget and known policy (truncate or reject), run classify() with over-budget input using stub provider client; assert either truncated payload length/token count <= budget or rejection occurs before any dispatch, per policy.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.4,"Integration":0.55,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"Provider-reported token usage for a typical document stays within the configured per-call budget.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Behavior requires provider-reported usage from real AI API execution path; mocks can trivially pass and hide real over-budget behavior (MOCK-HIDE=yes). Per rubric, tests that pass through real AI/ML API default to Agentic unless exclusively infrastructure-only; this behavior validates real provider token accounting, not just local routing, so LLM-DEP classification applies. MULTI-STEP=no. Rejection gate: Integration disqualified because stubbed usage counters would not detect provider-side tokenization/accounting drift; System-only framing is insufficient because dependency is specifically the real model API behavior.","test_description":"Execute real classification calls on representative documents, capture provider usage metadata for each call, and assert reported prompt/total tokens are <= configured budget threshold for the typical-document profile.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.0,"Integration":0.02,"System":0.28,"Agentic":0.68,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"When the API signals that the request rate is too high, the module waits and retries rather than returning an error to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Core failure boundary is retry orchestration between provider error handling, backoff/wait policy, and caller-facing return path (MOCK-MISS=yes). A stub provider can deterministically emit rate-limit errors then success; fake clock/sleeper can verify wait+retry without real network (REAL-INFRA=no). No dependence on model output content (LLM-DEP=no). No multi-agent chain (MULTI-STEP=no). Rejection gate: System disqualified because real network is not necessary to reproduce rate-limit control flow; Agentic disqualified because this is infrastructure behavior around the call, not model judgment.","test_description":"Wire classifier with stub provider sequence: rate-limit error on first K calls, valid response on next call; use controllable clock/backoff hook; assert module performs waits/retries and eventually returns success instead of surfacing immediate error.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.0}}]}
